Phoebus vouchsafe thy sacred Muse to lend</br>Pieria dames, your solemne tunes applie,</br>Aid sisters nine with me your deitie,</br>That to your seates these sacred notes may bend,</br>That you with me, and I with you may praise,</br>Elizas name and blisfull happie daies.

A Nymph more charie farre to gods than men,</br>Of gods belov'd.  O happy we that knowe,</br>O blisful soile where blossoms such do growe,</br>Unkindest earth that should not love hir then,</br>Unworthie much of hir that lov'd thee stil,</br>Whose love the gods accept with better wil.

People unkinde, but these that vertues prize,</br>You kinde by love do knowe what joy it is</br>To dwel on soile where peace yeeldes setled blis,</br>Unkind the rest too much that doe devize</br>To rue the soile, the seat, the state and al,</br>Of hir, for hirs that lives, and ever shal.

O Nature, wert thou now as firme on earth,</br>By equal mixture with the heavenly powers,</br>That in the soile where grewe such princely flowers,</br>The bravest blossome sprung by stately birth:</br>Now living stil might ever live on mould,</br>And never fade (O gods) that you so would.

Virtue be dombe, and never speake of grace,</br>And gracious Nymphs, that Virtues handmaides be,</br>Shrowde al at once your sweet eternitee:</br>Be Vertue now no more, nor in your space</br>Let grace be set without in large account,</br>O sacred Queene, thou others doost surmount.

Peace be thy nurse to feede thy happy yeares,</br>And endles Fame whereon thy throne is set,</br>To sound thy praise my Muse shal never let:</br>Live long, and raigne in joy among thy peeres,</br>Deare to the gods, to vertue, to thy soile,</br>Kept by thy grace from pray of forren spoile.</br>
